AZURE ENCRYPTION COMMANDS – EXPLANATION NOTES
=============================================

1) az account set --subscription "6f787beb-8095-4923-ae3e-deba86057045"

Purpose:
This command sets the active Azure subscription for the current Azure CLI session.

Explanation:
If a user has access to multiple subscriptions, Azure CLI needs to know
which subscription to run commands against. This command ensures that
all subsequent encryption, VM, and disk commands are executed in the
correct subscription.

Impact:
No configuration change is made to resources.
It only changes the CLI context.

------------------------------------------------------------

2) az feature register --name EncryptionAtHost --namespace Microsoft.Compute

Purpose:
Registers the EncryptionAtHost feature for the subscription.

Explanation:
Encryption at Host is a subscription-level feature that must be explicitly
registered before it can be used. This registration allows Azure to enable
host-level encryption for newly created virtual machines.

Important Notes:
- This is a one-time operation per subscription.
- Registration can take several minutes.
- EncryptionAtHost cannot be enabled on existing VMs.

------------------------------------------------------------

3) az feature show --name EncryptionAtHost --namespace Microsoft.Compute

Purpose:
Checks the registration status of the EncryptionAtHost feature.

Explanation:
This command is used to verify whether the EncryptionAtHost feature has
been successfully registered. The output will show a state such as:
- Registering
- Registered

Usage:
Only when the state is "Registered" can Encryption at Host be used.

------------------------------------------------------------

4) az disk show --resource-group firewall \
   --name myVm_OsDisk_1_12b00626cc9b403ca6dd4e540656011f \
   --query encryption.type --output tsv

Purpose:
Checks disk-level encryption at rest for the managed OS disk.

Explanation:
Azure Managed Disks are always encrypted at rest using Storage Service
Encryption (SSE). This command shows which key is used for encryption.

Possible Output Values:
- EncryptionAtRestWithPlatformKey
  (Microsoft-managed key – default)
- EncryptionAtRestWithCustomerKey
  (Customer-managed key using Disk Encryption Set)

This confirms encryption at rest at the storage layer.

------------------------------------------------------------

5) az vm show --resource-group firewall \
   --name myVm \
   --query securityProfile.encryptionAtHost --output tsv

Purpose:
Checks whether Encryption at Host is enabled for the virtual machine.

Explanation:
Encryption at Host ensures that all data stored on the VM host is encrypted
before being written to disk. This provides an additional layer of security
beyond standard disk encryption.

Output Meaning:
- true  → Encryption at Host is enabled
- false → Encryption at Host is not enabled

Important:
Encryption at Host can only be enabled at VM creation time.

------------------------------------------------------------

6) az disk show --resource-group firewall \
   --name myVm_OsDisk_1_12b00626cc9b403ca6dd4e540656011f \
   --query encryption

Purpose:
Displays the complete encryption configuration of the disk.

Explanation:
This command returns the full encryption object, including:
- Encryption type
- Disk Encryption Set ID (if CMK is used)
- Key source details

Use Case:
This is mainly used for security audits, compliance checks,
and detailed troubleshooting.

------------------------------------------------------------

SUMMARY
-------
- Azure Managed Disks are always encrypted at rest by default.
- EncryptionAtHost is an optional, additional security feature.
- Disk encryption and Encryption at Host are separate concepts.
- EncryptionAtHost must be registered at the subscription level.
- EncryptionAtHost cannot be enabled on an existing VM.

END OF NOTES
